## Cohort preview timeout — Lakebase connection resilience

Context: User reported the cohort preview ("Compute preview" button) was
hanging until the browser/proxy gave up. The server-side cohort engine
itself runs in <1 ms (logs: `CohortBuilder[…]: members=6 survivors=6
edges=0 cohorts=0 in 0ms`), yet the request took ~134 s end-to-end and
returned a stale-looking response. Root cause traced in the live log:

```
DEBUG | LakebaseAuth.password | Minted fresh Lakebase JWT for project ontobricks-app
DEBUG | store.load_global_config | load_global_config failed: consuming input
       failed: could not receive data from server: Operation timed out
SSL SYSCALL error: Operation timed out
INFO  | timing | POST /dtwin/cohorts/dry-run → 200 (133971.1ms)
```

The Lakebase pool's `_is_alive()` only checks client-side `conn.closed`;
when the Postgres server (or an intermediate proxy) silently dropped an
idle connection, the pool happily handed back the zombie socket. The
next `cur.execute()` then blocked at the OS TCP layer for ~130 s
(`tcp_retries2` default) before raising. Worst still, when the failure
finally surfaced, `GlobalConfigService.load()` overwrote the previously
good cache with `_empty()`, so every subsequent endpoint that resolves
the graph engine had to retry the slow path.

This was triggered repeatedly by a single rule edit because every
Stage 1 cohort endpoint calls `_cohort_get_store_and_graph()` →
`get_triplestore()` → `_resolve_graph_engine()` →
`GlobalConfigService.load()`.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/databricks/LakebaseAuth.py
   - `kwargs()` and `conninfo()` now emit libpq TCP keepalives:
     `keepalives=1, keepalives_idle=10, keepalives_interval=5,
     keepalives_count=3`. The OS now detects a server-side socket drop
     in ~25 s instead of ~130 s, so a dead pool entry surfaces as a
     normal exception (which the pool then evicts) rather than a
     multi-minute hang.

2. src/back/objects/session/GlobalConfigService.py
   - `_CACHE_TTL` bumped from 60 s → 300 s. The global config holds
     admin-only settings (warehouse_id, default_base_uri, graph_engine,
     etc.) that change rarely; a 5-minute cache reduces the frequency
     of cache-miss reads against Lakebase by ~5×.
   - Added `_STALE_CACHE_TTL = 30 minutes`. When `store.load_global_config()`
     raises, `load()` now returns the previously-cached config (if any
     and still inside the stale window) instead of falling back to
     `_empty()`. This stops a single Lakebase blip from cascading into
     dozens of slow requests across every endpoint that resolves the
     graph engine.

3. src/front/static/query/js/query-cohorts.js
   - `CohortModule.preview()` now wraps the dry-run fetch with an
     `AbortController` set to a 60 s budget. On timeout the user sees
     a clear message ("Preview timed out after 60s. The graph backend
     may be cold or busy — try again in a moment.") rendered into the
     preview panel, instead of an indefinite hang and a generic
     browser/proxy error.

4. tests/test_lakebase_auth.py
   - New `TestConnectionTuning` class with two regression tests pinning
     the TCP keepalive params on both `LakebaseAuth.kwargs()` and
     `LakebaseAuth.conninfo()`.

5. tests/test_graph_engine_config.py
   - New `TestGlobalConfigStaleWhileRevalidate` class with two
     regression tests:
     * a backend failure after a successful load returns the previous
       cache (not `_empty()`),
     * a backend failure with no prior cache still falls back to
       `_empty()` (no behaviour change in the cold-start path).

