## Frontend design rules — document the `ob-tabs` contract

Context: Right after rolling out the flat-underline tab style across
all tabbed sections, the design system doc still described tabs as
"Bootstrap nav-tabs, paired with `.ob-tab-content` for the bordered
pane" and had no enforcement language. New work (or a fresh
contributor) would happily reach for `<ul class="nav nav-tabs">`
again and get the legacy boxed look back. The convention needed to
become a written rule, not just a precedent in the code.

Changes:

1. .cursor/11-frontend-design.mdc
   - New section *Tabs (`.ob-tabs`) — flat-underline style*
     inserted between *Section Header & Top-Right Actions* and
     *Component Naming*. It documents:
     * the canonical `<ul class="nav nav-tabs ob-tabs"> + button +
       data-bs-toggle="tab" + tab-pane` skeleton,
     * the rule that **every** tab nav must combine
       `nav nav-tabs` and `ob-tabs`,
     * the icon-first label requirement,
     * the "font-size is intentionally inherited" contract (use
       Bootstrap `.small` for small tabs, scope one-off sizes to
       an area class — never override colour/padding/border in
       per-area files),
     * the catalogued `ob-tabs` combinations actually used by the
       codebase (Domain / Settings / Import / Wizard / DQ /
       Business Rules / Axioms / DT-DataQuality / DT-Inference),
     * the card-wrapping rule (drop `border-top-0 rounded-top-0`
       because `.nav-tabs.ob-tabs + .card` already neutralises the
       seam), and
     * an anti-patterns list (no bare nav-tabs, no pills, no
       per-area `.nav-link` redeclarations, no inline gap/font
       overrides, no hand-rolled tab JS, no edits to the legacy
       `.nav-tabs` block in `main.css`).
   - The *Component Naming* table now lists `ob-tabs` alongside
     `ob-tab-content` in the `ob-*` examples row.
   - The *Reusable Components Catalog* "Tabs" entry was rewritten
     to point to the new section instead of saying "Bootstrap
     nav-tabs". The legacy `.ob-tab-content` entry is kept but
     framed as the rare-case fallback.
   - The *What NOT to Do* checklist gains an entry: "Bare
     `<ul class="nav nav-tabs">` (no `ob-tabs`), pill tabs, or
     per-area redeclaration of `.nav-link` / `.nav-link.active`
     styles."

